# Project Rules for AI Coding Assistants Toolkit

## Repository Structure
- This is a documentation and tool collection repository
- All code examples should be well-commented and educational
- Maintain consistent formatting across all documentation files
- Use clear, descriptive file and folder names

## Documentation Standards
- Write documentation in Markdown format
- Include practical examples for all prompts and techniques
- Use code blocks with appropriate language syntax highlighting
- Add table of contents for longer documents
- Keep documentation concise but comprehensive

## Code Examples
- Provide complete, runnable code examples when possible
- Include both simple and advanced use cases
- Add comments explaining the reasoning behind specific approaches
- Use realistic but simplified examples that demonstrate the concept

## File Organization
- Group related prompts and techniques in dedicated folders
- Use consistent naming conventions across the repository
- Include README files in each major section
- Maintain a logical hierarchy of information

## Content Guidelines
- Focus on practical, actionable advice
- Include both beginner and advanced techniques
- Provide context for when to use specific approaches
- Keep content up-to-date with latest AI assistant features

## Quality Standards
- Test all code examples before including them
- Verify that prompts work as described
- Include troubleshooting tips for common issues
- Add version information for tool-specific content
